{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dowe_ver01/data/sn92073229/00332891868/1958030601/0179.xml":{"full_text":"THURSDAY\nISSUE\nNext Issue Monday\nVol. 35, No. 19\nCHAPEL HILL\nCHAFF\nBy Louis Graves\nThere are six persons >n\nChapel Hill now who would\nnot be here if Abraham\nLincoln had not been a kind\nhearted man.\nWhy this is so needs some\nexplaining.\nJohn McCaull, born in\nVirginia in 1844, joined Ma\nhone\u2019s Scouts of the Con\nfederate Army in the spring\nof 1861. He was a skilled\nhorseman already at the age\nof 17, daring, and resource\nful, and he received one\npromotion after another, so\nthat at the end of the war,\nwhen he was still short of\n21, he was a captain.\nA week or so before Ap\npomattox he had the bad\nluck to be captured by a\ntroop of Union cavalry. He\nwas taken to Richmond and\nput in prison. A few days\nafter he arrived there Lin\ncoln came on a visit to the\nConfederate eapitol. The\nprison was one of the places\nhe inspected and as he walk\ned along a corridor he saw\nthis youth sitting on a bench\nwith a guard over him, lean\ning over with his head in\nhis hands, a picture of utter\ndesolation.\n\u201cWhat\u2019s this boy doing\nhere?\u201d asked the President\nof the United States.\nThe officer who was es\ncorting him replied:\n\u201cHe was arrested while\nspying on us and he is going\nto lx; hanged tomorrow.\u201d\nYoung McCaull was not a\nspy. He was a Scout. There\nis a wide difference. A apy\nis disguised and pretends toi\nbe a neutral or an enemy\nsympathizer. He may even\nwear an enemy uniform to\n(Continued on Page 2)\nl I'.D.C. Meeting Tuesday\nThe United Daughters of the\nConfederacy will meet at 8 p.m.\u2019\nTuesday, March 11, with Mrs. C.\nW. Shields on Vance Street.\n(?cUtHcta.t\nEVENTS\nThursday, March 6\n7:30 p.m., Glenwood School\nFTA meets in school cafeteria.\n8 p.m., Richard Flint speaks,\n207 Venable Hall.\n8 p.m., PTSA Council meets,\nHigh School auditorium.\n8 p.m., Pharmacy Wives meet\nwith Mrs. W. J. Smith.\nFriday, March 7\n3 p m., Community Club meets,\nInstitute of Pharmacy.\nSaturday, March 8\n5:45 p.m., Fellowship supper\nat Oarrboro Baptist Church.\n6:30 p.m., International dinner\nsponsored by Cosmopolitan\nClub, Baptist Churrh basement.\nMonday, March 10\nMethodist circle meetings,\nschedule on page eight.\n3 p.m., Presbyterian women\nmeet at United Church.\ne 7:30 p.m., Urban Holmes\nspeaks on 12th and 13th Cen\ntury Houses in England and\nFrance,\" UNC Library\u2019s as\nsembly room.\n8 p.m., Ralph Marterie Band\ngives concert for benefit of\nChapel Hill Negro Communi\nty Center, Memorial Hall.\nP\u00bb 8 p.m., Robert Hughes apeaks\nto open meeting of Association\nfor Retarded Children, at Cha\npel Hill High School.\n\nMorehead Planetarium: \u201cDev\nils, Demons and Stars,\u201d 8:30\np.m. daily plus 11 a.m., 3 p.m.\nSat. and 3 .p.m., 4 p.m. Sun.\n\nVarsity Theatre: Thur., Fri.,\n\u201cNana, a French Coquette,\"\nCharles Boyer, Martine Carol;\nSat. late show, Sun., Mon., \u201cWit\nness for the Prosecution,\u201d Tyrone\nPower, Marlene Dietrich, Charles\nLaughton (feature begins at 1\np.m., 3:09 p.m., 5:18 p.*., 7:27\np.m., 9:36 p.m.), j\nCarolina Theatre: Opens Thurs\nday, \u201cRaintree County,\u201d Mont\ngomery Cltft Elisabeth Taylor,\nEva Maria Saint (shears begin\nat 1 p.m., 3:44 p.nu, 4:38 p.m., 1\n9:12 p.m.).\n5 Centa a Copy\nPNC Gift\nEnlarged\nBy Donor\nMorehead Notes\nHigh Caliber\nOs Candidates\nJohn Motley Morehead person\nally awarded $175,000 worth of\nUniversity scholarships to 35\ncarefully selected high school\nseniors here this week and de\nclared his intent to \u201csubstantial\nly increase and expand\u201d the\nMorehead Foundation for U.N.C.\nscholarships to talented students\nso that the program can be guar\nanteed in the future. Each of\nthe 35 young men will receive\n$5,000 for his four-year educa\ntion here.\nA Tar Heel native and Uni\nversity alumnus, Mr. Morehead\nhelped found the Union Carbide\nand Carbon Company. He made\nhis decision to increase the worth\nof the foundation after he had\nconsidered the 35 candidates\ncorning before its trustees. He\nI was so impresed by them that\ninstead of eliminating several of\nthe students, as planned, he\nagreed to add to the foundation\nand accept all 35 Morehead\nScholars.\nThis week's selection was the\nlargest number of undergraduate\nMorehead Scholars yet chosen\nsince Mr. Morehead first began\nmaking the awards in 1951.\nMethodists Will l\nI\nOpen Bids On\nProposed Wing I\nWill the University Methodist\ni Church begin to build its educa\ntional wing this spring? That 1\nquestion will be decided by\nMarch 19 when bids will be open\nled by the building committee of\nthe church.\nThe original wing was to have\ncost $250,000 and a fund drive\nwas undertaken to pay for it.\nSince not enough cash has been\ncollected to undertake that proj\nect, the architect was asked to\ndraw up plans retaining the\noriginal exterior but eliminating\nabout $76,000 worth of the in\nside work, work that could be\npostponed until a later date. Thn\nwas done and all bids are expect\n-led to be in by the 19th. If a\ncontractor is willing to do the\njob a.i outlined for about $175,-\n000, construction will probably\nbegin this spring.\nI\nNewcomers Club\nElects Officers\ni\nMrs. Datfid Duncan was elect\ned president of the Faculty New\ncomers Club at a recent meeting\nof the club. She will succeed\nMrs. Troy Sluder. Other offi\ncers for the coming year are\nMrs. Edward Foster, vice-presi\ndent; Mrs. John Eyre, secretary,\n!and Mrs. Richard Levin, treas\nurer.\nThe following committee\nchairmen were appointed by Mrs.\n*D uncan: Mrs. Robin Higham,\npublicity; Mrs. Charles Starling,\nprogram; Mrs. J. Boyd Flynn,\nsocial, and Mrs. James Hickey\nand Mis. John Lacey, activities-\nRed Cross to Begin\nDrive Thifc Sunday\nThe American Red Cross fund\ndrive in the Chapel Hill-Carri>oro\nCommunity will begin this Sun\nday with a house-to-house can\nvass by volunteer workers. The\ncanvass will continue through\nSaturday, March 15. Everybody\nis atked to give a friendly re\nception to the volunteer workers!\nand to contribute generously to\nthis most worthy causa.\nDrive committee chairmen are\nMiss Maude Lee, residential;\nWebb Evans, University staff;\nJoe Robbins, business; Mrs.\nI Claude Baker, Cantwro; Don\nStanford, rural; Henry Atwater,\nNegro community; Mias Cornelia\nS. Love, special gifts, and Ty\nBoyd, publicity.\nRalph Howard is chairman of\nof the drive.\nThe Chapel Hill Weekly\nEDUCATION\nWeekly Offers\nSpecial Report On Conflicting Roles\nIn The University\u2019s Administration\nBy Bob Mirandon\nFor the past few days the controversy over the ap\nparently conflicting roles of the Consolidated Universi\nty\u2019s Board of Trustees and the State Board of Higher\nEducation has died down to a polite level, but everybody\nwho has followed the situation knows that the two\npowerful bodies again will clash in the future.\nWhy is it almost inevitable that this will happen?\nThis series of articles in the Weekly will give the back\nground of the State Board of Education, describe its\nI designated role, and try to throw 4\nsome light upon the controversy.\nThe ostensible cause of the re\nj cent short-lived battle between\nthe U. N. C. trustees and the\niState Board stems from a matter\nof housing facilities for married\nstudents at State College in Ra\nleigh. The trustees at a meet\ning two weeks ago in Greens-'\nI boro recommended a 500-unit\nhousing project for State, which\nwas to be a self-liquidating proj\nect financed by a bond issue.\nHowever, the State Board of\nHigher Education previously had\nrefused to approve the trustees\u2019\n'proposal in its entirety and had\nChuck Wagon Restaurant To Open\nSoon Next Door To Post Office\nI\nI H\nmmWU\n\u25a0\u2018,y*\nI HPI W\nI I ;W^M\nI I I I\nII I\" I\nHEBB\nV\nf W c.. Ts\n,iv*' \u00a3W'\u00abik*~\u00a3' r MrnHKm -B^ 1\nm JB\nGETTING THE (HIIKK WAGON READY\u2014Don Belton,\nabove, owner of the Western style Chuck Wagon Restaurant\nwhich will have its grand opening soon, is shout U> enter the\neating place, which is next to the Foot Office. The ivstaurant is\nbeing remodeled now to create an authentic Wastern atmosphere.\nMr. Belton also own* and operate* the Carolina Coffee Shop.\nA new restaurant, the Chuck\nWagon, with authentic Westerh\nstyle food and Western ranch\natmosphere, will open soon next\nto the Post Office. It will be\nowned and operated by Don Bel- i\nton, owner and operator of the i\nCarolina Coffee Shop. ii\nMr. Belton said he waa ae\npleased with the response of the\nServing the Chapel Hill Area Sinee 1923\nCHAPEL HILL, N. C., THURSDAY, MARCH 6. 1958\nrecommended only a 300-uait\nproject. Apparently the'reason\ni for the State Board's objection\nto the 500-unit plan was baaed j\non its feeling that a major\nI policy decision was involved\nwhich should be considered by!\nthe General Assembly before ac-1\ntion was taken. Also it was said\nthat prospective enrollment dnl|\nnot justify a housing project of i\nthis size. Yesterday the State\nBoard repeated this reasoning in\na written statement.\nAt this point the howls of the\ntrustees began. University Trus\n(Continued on page 12\nmany customers at the Carolina\nCoffee Shop during his first\nyear\u2014there were about 182,000\nmeals served\u2014that he was\nprompted to think of a special\nty house \"with the kind of mood\nand decor that Chapel Hill now\ndoes not have.\" Por some time\nMr. Belton considered opening a\n(Continued on Page It)\nRobert Hughes\nWill Give Talk\nMonday Evening\nKobart Hughes of the Uni-j\n|\u00bb'ty\u2019s School of Education 1\nspeak at an open meeting\nof the Orange County Associa\ntion for Retarded Children at 8\np.m. Monday, March 10, at the\nChxpel Hill High School. He\nwill discuss the training and ed\nucation of retarded children and\nthe preparation of adults for\nwork in this field.\nMr. Hughes recently came to}\nChapel Hill from the University\nof Illinois, where he completed,\nhis training as a psychologist in\nthe field of the exceptional;\nchild. Here at U.N.C. he has\nbeen assigned the project of de\nveloping a training program for\nspecial education teachers.\nThe Association is now con j\nducting a county-wide survey in\nan effort to locate all retarded\nchildren in Orange County. The\nwork is being carried out through\nvarious agencies. A'l parents or\nrelatives are urged to cooperate\nby answering and returning the\ninquiries sent them, so that the\nAssociation may be better able\nto determine the need and carry\nout its desire to establish com\nmunity facilities throughout the\ncounty.\nGasoline Prices\nEdging Back lip\nAlthough the price of gasoline\nis lower than it was before the\nprice war was started several\nweeks ago, it has risen to 30.0\ncents for regular gasoline and\n34.0 cents for high test gasoline.\nOnly one of several service sta\ntions checked by the Weekly yes-,\nterday sold gasoline higher.\nThere regular gasoline sold for\n31.9 cents and high test also\nsold for one cent more per gml\nlon.\n'Hie oil dealers had no expla\nnation for the rapid flux in the\nprice of gasoline which had\ndipped to 26.0 cents and even\nlower at some stations two\nweeks ago. Trade publications\nhad mentioned a surplus of gaso\nlina and that by some was givsn\nas the possible reason for the\nprice war. However, that could\nhardly be the cause for the sud\nden rise in gasoline prices, a\nspokesman for one of the oil\ndealers said. The gasoline deal\ners are apparently as penplexed\nby the change in price of gaso\nline as are the service station\noperators and the public.\nInspection at Northside\nThe final inspection of the new\neight-room classroom addition to\nthe Northside Elementary Bchool\nwill be held at I p.m. this Fri-j\ndny.\nElection On School\nMerger Is Requested\nCommunity Chest\nNearer Its Goal\nThe follow-up 1958 Chapel Hill,\nCommunity Chest drive increased j\nfrom 57 per cent to 72 per cent\nthe amount of the budgeted ob-\njective collected by over 200\nvolunteer solicitors.\nArea captains reported yester-1\nday that $4,332.10 was raised\nbetween March 2 and 4. The\ngoaj of the drive, originally un\ndertaken last fall, was $28,767. J\nSo, at this point the Chest lacks\n$7,781.74 of attaining its goal.\nChest treasurer Gordon Perry j\nJr. emphasized that figures for\nthe second drive are \u201cby no\nmeans final. Quite a few col\nlectors were unable to report in\nyesterday and, of course, checks\nwill continue to arrive' in the\nmail.\u2019\u2019 i\nDr. Frank Williams, chairman\nof the Division of Health Af\nfairs solicitation, said that \u201cper\nhaps only 75 per cent of the\namount expected here has been\nreceived and reported.\u201d In other\nareas, final reports are expected\nby the weekend.\nIn the residential areas, re\nports are still forthcoming from\nnumerous solicitors, and the bus\niness firms division report is\nonly 10 per cent complete.\nAt yesterday\u2019s meeting area\ncaptains reported collections\nfrom an estimated 75 per cent\nof their collectors. According\nto Mrs. Emil Chanlett, however,\nthis does not indicate that the\ncollections will increase by 25\nper cent.\nHere Is Voting Procedure For\ni w\nProposed School Merger Plan\nThe Orange County Board of\nEducation at its March meeting\nlust Monday decided to ask the\niCounty Board of Commissioners\nto permit the people of Carrboro\nand White Cross to vote whether\nthey want to join the Chapel Hill\nSchool District, accepted bids of\nsll ,600 for a principal\u2019s home\nat Cedar Grove, and accepted\nlow bids totaling $207,000 for\nadditions to the Efland, the\nEfland-Cheek and the Cedar\ndrove Schools.\nIn voting to accept the recom\nmendation of delegations from\nCan-boro and White Cross to\noverride the majority opinion of\nthe Carrboro School Committee\nand permit the people of those\ncommunities to vote whether\nthey want to join the Chapel Hill\nSchool District, the Board ended\na three year struggle of Carr\nboro citizens to settle the ques\ntion. 1\nCharles Davis, superintendent 1\nof Chapel Hill City Schools, and\nPaul Carr, superintendent of the\nOrange County Schools, will\nI w ithin a week draw u(> the exact\nboundaries of the Carrboro and\nWhite Cross district that is to\nvote on the question.\nThe joint petition by the two\nIf There Is A Recession Here\nNobody Seems To Know About It\n\u201cBeing a salaried town, we\u2019ll\nj be slow in feeling any recession,\u201d\nsaid William E. Thompson, exec\nutive vice-president of the Bank\n\u2022>f Chapel Hill, in summing up\nhis statements that Chapel Hill\nhas not as yet had any symptoms\nof a recession.\nReal estate spokesmen gave\nanother reason for Chapel Hill\u2019s\nnot feeling signs of the nation\nwide recession: Almost daily\npeople are moving into Chapel\nHill. This keeps the reel estate\nmarket up even if other forces\nwere at work to bring it down.\nThe Research Triangle is another\nforce that will probably ward\noff a depression in this area, ac\ncording to the real estate peo\nple\nThe Carrboro Milts are op\nerating full force five days s\nweek and during February had\nto run six days one week to\nmeet orders- Salaries are up\nand orders are high, a mill\ni lie Oriuege County Building\n**d Lean A\u2014riatlaw b a* far]\n$4 a Year in County; other rates on pat* t\ni Solicitations on the campus,\nj headed by Charles Bernard, re\nportedly are 60 per cent com\nplete.\nWhile all signs point to a\nfairly substantial increase of\ncollections over the 72 per cent\nto date, Mr. Perry cautioned\nthat experience shows that\npledges are not honored to the\nextent most people realize. AID\nthe figures quoted in this story\ninclude both cash and pledges.\nA final report from the Chapel\nHill Community Council on the\nresult of both last fall\u2019s initial\ni Community Chest drive and the\nfollowup conducted this week\nwill be issued soon.\nDick Young, who headed the\ndrive last fall and is assisting in\nI the current phase of it, made a\nparticularly strong point that\nthe failure to reach the goal in\nthe second drive was not caused\nby the lack of effort on the part\nof solicitors.\n\u201cThe solicitors were not only\nj conscientious but extremely ac\ntive in seeking out every mem-\nI ber of the community who was\nnot approached during the first\ndrive,\u201d said Mr. Young.\nOther Community Council of\nficials joined in his praise of the\nthoroughness of the second solic\nitation. All meetings and ses\nsions, which were a vital part of\nthe preparation of the second\ndrive, were well attended and\nadvice on techniques on solicita\ntion was well heeded.\nschool boards has been printed,\nand is ready to be signed as soon\ni, as the above boundaries are\nI established and inserted. It will\nthen be necessary to advertise\nthe election and have registra\ntion polls open for three weeks\nfor registration and an additional\nII week for challenge of vote. The\nregistration will be necessary\nsince no present political unit\ncoincides with the area that will\n'vote on this school issue.\nAlthough K. J. M. Hobbs,\nchairman of the Orange County\ni Commissioners, indicated that it\n1 is probable that the voting will\ntake place May 31, the date of\nthe primaries, Charles Stanford,\u2019\nchairman of the Orange County\nSchool Board, said that the\nvoting would probably not take\nplace on that date but would be\nheld within a day or two of that\ntime. In either case, the deci-,\nsion of the voters will affect!\nthe operation of the schools this\nfall.\nBecause of the current laws,;\nthe Chapel Hill School District!\npeople will have to bear the cost\nof the registration for the vote\non this issue even though Chapel\nHill people will not vote on this\nissue. i\ndoing more business in 1058 than\nwas done in the early months of\n1957. \u201cWe have $250,000 in\ncommittments and loans, so we\ncan\u2019t see signs of a recession,\u201d\nan officer of the Association said.\nThe local merchants have the\nsame good news: There is no)\nsign of a recession here. Gro\ncery stores raport higher earn\nings for the stores and for the\nemployees. The furniture store\nowners reported that business\nwas better last week than in\nsome time. \u201cThat may be due\nto the bad winter weather we\u2019ve\nhad,\" said one furniture dealer.\nOther merchants tell the same\nstory. Thera is no recession\nhere. Commercial, industrial,\nand salary incomes are definitely\nup in this area.\nMrs. Childress Recovering\nMrs. Paul Childress, tks daugh\nter of Mr. and Mrs. J. W, Clark\nSr- of High Street in Carrboro,\nis rwenptng in a Greensboro\nhospital after a serious eperatios\nlist Mosdiji\n7\nNotoiy has a right t\u00ab da as ha\npfeaaaa writes ha pteaaaa to to\nright.\nProposed Plan\n\nMay Be Opposed\nIn Carrboro\nThe Orange County Board of\nEducation last Monday Anally\npassed a resolution to ask she\nCounty Commissioners for an\nelection in Carrboro and White\nCross to decide whether these\ndistricts will merge with the\nChapel Hill school unit,\" At the\nsame time, however, it appears\nthat a group of Carrboro citi\nzens art organizing opposition\nto a merger.\nA delegation of Cariboro resi\ndents representing the town\u2019s\nCitizens Committee for Schools\nappeared before the County\nboard to request an election some\ntime before July 1, the end of\nthe current fiscal year. The\nCounty school board made a ver\nbal request to the Commission\ners on Monday afternoon.\nIf the merger is approved, the\nChapel Hill special tax district\nwill be extended and Carrboro\nand White Croat residents will\nhave to pay a 15-cent school tax.\nAt present these towns sand\n.white high school studsnts and all\nj Negro students to Chxpel HQI\nschools. Chapel Hillisna pay a\n115-cent school tax, but CarriKWQ\nand White Cross residents do\nj not.\nMonday night the County and\nI Chapel Hill soheo! boards Met\ntogether to <ti tones the Matter.\nChairman Greg Cuibreth said the\nChapel Hill board gave its unan\nimous endorsement to the efo-\nI tion.\nCw*. superintendent of\n.the Orange County Schools, told\nthe board moiaJtdu that the\nCoenty ltfnM) n MMtolll\ntake final action on 1\nplans until a formal, written re\nquest is made to them. A draft\nof the request has beeh written,\nhe noted, but it will be necessarjf\nito decide on the exact voting\nareas. Mr. Carr and Charles\nW. Davis, Chapel Hill superin\ntendent of schools, will decide on\nthe proper areas to be included\nin the voting. The law requires\nthe Chapel Hill school board to\npay the cost of the election.\nR. J. M. Hobbs, chairman of\nthe County Board of Commis\nsioners, said that as soon as a\njoint petition is received from\nthe Chapel Hill and County\nschool boards the Elections\nBoard will be asked to call for\na vote on the issue. It must be\nnine weeks from the time of the\nrequest before an election can\nbe held, he noted. For this rea\nson the school boards will have\nno time to waste if the vote is\nto be held on May 31, the day\nof the Democratic primaries.\nAlso there will have to be a\nspecial registration, Mr. flobbs\nsaid, since the area and the issue\ninvolved will have no relation to\nother elections at that time.\nMr. Carr also said he had been\nrequested to tell the Chapel Hill\nboard there is some organised\nopposition to the merger in Carr\nboro. This opposing group in\ncludes residents who formerly\nwere in favor of a 15-cent tax\n(Continued on page 12)\nchapel hill\nScenes\ndescribing in word or two\nwhat your friends are say\ning- thinking, and doing\nMRS. EDDIE GILL tolling of\nseeing TYRONE POWER at tha\nChapel of St. Thomas More.\nROY HOLSTEN suffering a\nsprained ankle. ERNEST\nHEARN opposing Cartiwro\u2019a\njoining the Chapel Kill School\nDistrict. .MRS. BRUCE RIGGS\nBEE advocating Carrboro\u2019s join\ning the Chapel Hill School Diat\nrict. .PATROLMAN CHARLES\n,LRE BYRD helping children\nacross the street. .MAXINE\nFITCH getting in touch with\nwomen to servo on ooan*ftt#o\nfor the Methodist Church Ba~\n\u00abaar. .MRS. TYNDALL HAIL\nRiS arranging to sell BAM bone*\nof Girl Scout cookies. .ERLE\nPEACOCK JR. finding laM\n\u2022ter hi. mw daughter. JUMP\njNYB busily aetllag reoerda Hho\nIkftliflJMMe","height":"26338","width":"19943"}}
